port. Several key steps are represented too coarsely, especially aminonitrile formation from triose chemistry and tetrose-to-thioester conversion. The hydrothermal formate-to-formaldehyde step is weaker than the rest of the network, and the Mg-porphin route is too speculative to support the target strongly. A notable schema-level issue is that the summary provided does not show mineral agents for hydrothermal and surface reactions, even though these are required by the original design constraints; this lowers environmental rigor. Literature alignment is overall good conceptually, but reaction-level support would be stronger with explicit Cu photoredox participation, thiol-catalyzed rearrangement details, and acknowledgment of stereochemical and degradation challenges documented in the research.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.87\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.88, "rxn_002": 0.58, "rxn_003": 0.86, "rxn_004": 0.88, "rxn_005": 0.84, "rxn_006": 0.72, "rxn_007": 0.82}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.79, "pathway_coherence": 0.86, "environmental_progression": 0.9, "target_achievement": 0.84, "overall_confidence": 0.84, "feedback": "Strong overall hydrothermal-to-surface route consistent with literature emphasis on vent-fixed C1 feedstocks feeding cyanosulfidic homologation. The weakest step is the explicit hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde, which is less securely established than CO2-to-formate chemistry. The cyanosulfidic sequence to glycolaldehyde/glyceraldehyde and the aminonitrile-to-threonine logic are literature-aligned, though the direct lumping of triose-derived chemistry into one aminonitrile-forming step simplifies a more complex branch network.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006"], "suggestions": ["Downgrade rxn_002 to a more explicitly speculative C1 reduction step or replace with a better-supported 