,\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_023\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H16N2O7P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"L-alanyl-L-threonine phosphate adduct\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanyl-threonine dipeptide precursor\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions, H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface electron transfer reduces CO2 with H2 to surface-bound formyl/formate equivalents that desorb as formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Iron-sulfur vent chemistry strongly supports CO2 reduction to formate under alkaline hydrothermal conditions, furnishing reduced carbon that can feed surface chemistry after transport. This is consistent with iron-sulfur world and vent carbon-fixation literature summarized in the report (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction of formate to formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"subseafloor rock-water interaction; speculative connecting step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further reduction of C1 oxycarbon species on reduced iron/mineral surfaces yields more reduced aldehydic carbon.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report emphasizes hydrothermal generation of reduced carbon feedstocks and organics from serpentinization/iron-rich systems but does not document a single definitive formate-to-formaldehyde experiment for threonine chemistry. This step is therefore included as a necessary, explicitly speculative connector between hydrothermal C1 fixation and surface aldol/cyanosulfidic chemistry, while remaining compatible with Fe0/magnetite-mediated reduction environments (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom & Seewald, 2007; speculative connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal mineral interface\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Successive mineral-catalyzed carbon fixation and C-C bond-forming reductions furnish alpha-keto acid products including pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research summary specifically lists hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite as a key reaction type and situates alpha-keto acids as metabolically central hubs for early chemistry. This reaction introduces a hydrothermal keto-acid node that can feed later biochemical transformations (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite and greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate forms an imine with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to alanine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on mineral surfaces is directly aligned with the hydrothermal network described in the instructions and the report's emphasis on alpha-keto acids and amino-acid production under vent conditions. Alanine then serves as a plausible amine donor in non-enzymatic transamination-like biochemical coupling (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type carbon fixation to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic hydrothermal vent conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface-bound CO hydrogenation and C-C coupling generate reduced C2 carboxylates including acetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report situates transition-metal sulfides and hydrothermal carbon fixation as a robust source of reduced carbon compounds. Acetate provides an additional hydrothermal carbon reservoir supporting environmental interconnection and carbon-flow redundancy (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Cody et al., 2000).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox system with mineral-assisted concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; cyanosulfidic surface flow chemistry; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven Cu photoredox reduction/homologation of HCN in the presence of sulfide generates C2 aldehyde products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN under cyanosulfidic conditions as the core engine of the Sutherland network and specifically notes glycolaldehyde as a primary homologation product. Surface minerals are included to satisfy the environmental requirement and reflect concentration/photocatalytic support in shallow settings (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox system with mineral-assisted concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; flow-chemistry compatible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further photoredox homologation of cyanide-derived C2 carbonyl intermediates affords triose aldehyde products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly states that glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde arise through UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN in the cyanosulfidic network. This is one of the central experimentally supported branches leading toward threonine precursor chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface isomerization of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-assisted stabilization and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reported within cyanosulfidic sugar network; dihydroxyacetone observed at 59% yield from glyceraldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbonyl migration/isomerization equilibrates triose aldehyde and ketone forms, with mineral matrices stabilizing reactive sugars.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes conversion of glyceraldehyde to the more stable isomer dihydroxyacetone at 59% yield in simulated cyanosulfidic environments. Borate stabilization of sugars and mineral concentration are directly compatible with surface prebiotic settings (Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; Patel et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface branching from triose chemistry to threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox-compatible cyanosulfidic regime with clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed shallow pools or flow chemistry; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Triose-derived carbonyl species undergo cyanide addition and amination to furnish the alpha-aminonitrile 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile as a branch product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile is an 'inevitable byproduct' of the same cyanosulfidic chemistry that yields triose sugars and that it is the Strecker precursor of threonine. This reaction therefore represents the key literature-grounded branch point rather than an invented alternative route (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay concentration and phosphate-buffered wet-dry cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"shallow pool hydrolysis after concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydration and amidic hydrolysis convert the alpha-aminonitrile into the free amino acid threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although the report emphasizes the aminonitrile as the immediate Strecker precursor, hydrolysis to the free amino acid is the standard completion of alpha-aminonitrile chemistry and is necessary to connect the experimentally observed precursor to the target. This is a conservative completion step consistent with prebiotic Strecker chemistry and the report's framework (Miller, 1957; Patel et al., 2015; necessary connecting step).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to tetrose sugar pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ammonia-catalyzed aldol chemistry with borate stabilization and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"moderate pH around 5.2; wet-dry compatible\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia-catalyzed aldol addition of C1 and C2 aldehydes produces a tetrose mixture including erythrose, threose, and erythrulose, stabilized by borate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report's prebiotic sugar pathway explicitly begins with aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to tetrose sugars under milder conditions than classic formose chemistry, catalyzed by ammonia or amino acids and aided by concentration mechanisms. This is the core entry to the thioester route (Powner et al., 2009; Islam & Powner, 2017 as summarized in the report; ammonia-catalyzed prebiotic sugar pathway).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to tetrose sugar pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate-stabilized aldol condensation on clay-rich surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol coupling between C2 and C3 carbonyl compounds expands the sugar pool to tetroses.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The instructions highlight aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to sugars, and this route is compatible with the report's broader sugar-centered threonine chemistry. It provides a second convergent route to the tetrose hub using cyanosulfidic products already documented in the report (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012; connected literature-consistent extension).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface dehydration of tetrose pool to alpha-ketoaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"clay-assisted dehydration with sugar-stabilizing borate\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mildly acidic to near-neutral drying phases\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Beta-dehydration of tetrose sugars generates an alpha-ketoaldehyde intermediate poised for N/S addition chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report explicitly describes beta-dehydration of tetroses to alpha-ketoaldehydes as a required mechanistic step in the prebiotic sugar pathway to threonine thioesters. This reaction is therefore included at full granularity rather than compressed (prebiotic sugar pathway literature summarized in the report; Islam & Powner, 2017-style mechanism).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface thiol-assisted adduct formation and redox rearrangement to activated threonine thioester\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\