re rapidly at hydrothermal temperatures above about 120 degrees C (prebiotic sugar pathway summary in the report; kinetic stability constraints summarized from FT-IR degradation studies).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical peptidization of activated threonine thioester with alanine-derived amine partner\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_023\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling; phosphate-assisted activation in concentrated films\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Activated thioester acyl transfer to an amino component furnishes a peptide-like adduct, preserving threonine within assembling proto-biopolymers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report notes that the activated threonine thioester may react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth, solving part of the activation problem. Alanine is supplied from hydrothermal reductive amination, explicitly linking hydrothermal and surface products into biochemical assembly (prebiotic sugar pathway summary in the report; Forsythe et al., 2015 for wet-dry peptide relevance).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical release of threonine from peptide-like adduct\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_023\", \"mol_021\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"reversible pool chemistry and partial hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Partial hydrolysis of the peptide-like intermediate liberates threonine while regenerating alanine and phosphate components.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is a necessary network-connecting extension that reflects reversible prebiotic oligomerization and hydrolysis in fluctuating pools. It provides an additional literature-consistent route from activated threonine chemistry to free threonine without contradicting the report (Forsythe et al., 2015; necessary connecting step).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface phosphorylation-compatible cyanamide formation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-rich evaporitic surface with photochemical input\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"speculative connector reflecting mutual compatibility with nucleotide chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrogen-rich cyanide chemistry under photochemical/phosphate-rich conditions produces cyanamide-like condensing agents.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically mentions cyanamide as mutually compatible with amino-acid and ribonucleotide precursor chemistry but does not supply a full dedicated synthetic route in the threonine context. This reaction is therefore included as a clearly marked speculative connector that integrates the broader systems chemistry without displacing the core threonine routes (Patel et al., 2015; speculative connector).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic aminonitrile route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN undergoes UV-driven reductive homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, which branch to the threonine aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic route through dihydroxyacetone branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The triose pool isomerizes to dihydroxyacetone before feeding the same branch chemistry that yields threonine aminonitrile and threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C1 feed to sugar-thioester route\",\n      \"description\": \"Vent-generated formate is reduced to formaldehyde, which combines with surface glycolaldehyde to produce tetroses that are converted through alpha-ketoaldehyde and activated threonine thioester to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol-thioester route from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde undergo ammonia-catalyzed tetrose formation, followed by dehydration and thiol-assisted redox rearrangement to activated threonine thioester and hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol-thioester route from glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"A second sugar-assembly route to the tetrose pool starts from cyanosulfidic C2/C3 sugars and converges on the same thioester