e) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_011, mol_012, mol_013 -> mol_014 (Surface thiol-assisted adduct formation and redox rearrangement to activated threonine thioester) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_014, mol_021 -> mol_016 (Biochemical hydrolysis of activated threonine thioester to threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_016: mol_014, mol_018, mol_019 -> mol_023 (Biochemical peptidization of activated threonine thioester with alanine-derived amine partner) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_017: mol_023, mol_021 -> mol_016, mol_018, mol_019 (Biochemical release of threonine from peptide-like adduct) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_018: mol_005, mol_012 -> mol_006 (Surface phosphorylation-compatible cyanamide formation) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Canonical cyanosulfidic aminonitrile route (4 steps)\n  - P2: Cyanosulfidic route through dihydroxyacetone branch (5 steps)\n  - P3: Hydrothermal C1 feed to sugar-thioester route (7 steps)\n  - P4: Surface aldol-thioester route from formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde (4 steps)\n  - P5: Surface aldol-thioester route from glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde (6 steps)\n  - P6: Hybrid hydrothermal-surface cyanosulfidic route (6 steps)\n  - P7: Deep sugar-pool route via dihydroxyacetone and tetrose convergence (7 steps)\n  - P8: Activated thioester to peptide to threonine release route (5 steps)\n  - P9: Fully integrated vent-to-peptide route (10 steps)\n  - P10: Systems-chemistry route with cyanamide-compatible surface chemistry (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_007, mol_008, mol_010, mol_015, mol_014\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine: Geochemical Pathways, Catalytic Mechanisms, and Environmental ContextsThe quest to identify the prebiotic origins of threonine ($C_{4}H_{9}NO_{3}$) represents a distinctive challenge within the broader field of chemical evolution, as this molecule occupies a unique structural niche among the twenty proteinogenic amino acids. Unlike simpler counterparts such as glycine or alanine, threonine possesses two chiral centers, a property shared only by isoleucine, which creates four possible stereoisomeric configurations: (2S,3R)-L-threonine, (2R,3S)-D-threonine, (2S,3S)-L-allothreonine, and (2R,3R)-D-allothreonine. In contemporary biochemistry, threonine serves as a vital component of protein structures, a site for post-translational phosphorylation by kinases, and a precursor to the biosynthesis of glycine and isoleucine. The abiotic emergence of such a complex molecule requires a specific convergence of four-carbon backbone assembly, functional group placement, and stereochemical control, all of which must occur under the volatile and often harsh conditions of the Hadean Earth. Research over the past several decades has shifted from generalized spark-discharge models toward highly specific, systems-level chemical networks that emphasize the compatible origins of threonine alongside ribonucleotides and lipid precursors.The Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism and Reductive HomologationA leading theoretical framework for the synthesis of threonine is the cyanosulfidic prebiotic scenario, pioneered by John Sutherland and his colleagues. This model moves beyond the traditional \"prebiotic soup\" hypothesis to propose a systems chemistry approach, where the foundational components of life emerge simultaneously from a common set of precursors under a unified geochemical regime. The central chemical engine of this system is the reductive homologation of hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$), driven by ultraviolet (UV) radiation and facilitated by hydrogen sulfide ($H_{2}S$) as a stoichiometric reductant.Mechanisms of Backbone AssemblyIn the cyanosulfidic network, threonine synthesis is intricately linked to the formation of ribonucleotide precursors. The process begins with the UV-driven reductive homologation of $HCN$ to produce glycolaldehyde ($C_{2}$) and glyceraldehyde ($C_{3}$). Within this network, threonine is produced as a branched byproduct of the reactions leading to sugar assembly. Specifically, the $\\alpha$-aminonitrile Strecker precursor of threonine\u20142-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\u2014is formed as an \"inevitable byproduct\" of the same chemistry that yields triose sugars like glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone.The reaction utilizes $Cu(I)-Cu(II)$ photoredox cycling to accelerate carbon-carbon bond formation. This copper-mediated chemistry allows for the efficient conversion of simple one-carbon feedstocks into the more complex four-carbon chain required for threonine. The presence of copper is essential, as it coordinates with cyanide and sulfur species to stabilize reactive intermediates that would otherwise decompose in an aqueous environment. The system's plausibility is enhanced by its reliance on common volcanic and meteoritic reagents, such as $HCN$, $H_{2}S$, and phosphate, delivered periodically through geochemical events.Yields and Precursor RelationshipsData from simulated cyanosulfidic environments indicates that these reactions are kinetically feasible, producing high yields of key intermediates. For instance, the conversion of glyceraldehyde to its more stable isomer, dihydroxyacetone, occurs at a 59% yield, while subsequent steps leading to lipid and amino acid precursors show consistent efficiency. The threonine precursor nitrile (compound 16 in the Sutherland nomenclature) emerges from the triose-derived building blocks alongside the precursors for glycine, alanine, and serine.Precursor MoleculeTarget ProductRole in SynthesisYield/ObservationHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Glycolaldehyde$C_{2}$ feedstockPrimary homologation product GlyceraldehydeDihydroxyacetone$C_{3}$ intermediate59% Yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrileThreonineStrecker precursor\"Inevitable byproduct\" CyanamideRibonucleotidesCondensing agentMutual compatibility with AAs The spatial and temporal separation of these reactions is addressed by the \"flow-chemistry\" model. In this scenario, chemical evolution occurs along a planetary surface (such as a river with multiple tributaries), where different pH, temperature, and mineral gradients allow for the sequential addition of reagents without causing the global destruction of fragile intermediates.The Prebiotic Sugar Pathway and Activated ThioestersAn alternative and complementary pathway for threonine synthesis is the Prebiotic Sugar Pathway, which emphasizes the role of simple aldehydes\u2014formaldehyde ($HCHO$) and glycolaldehyde ($HOCH_{2}CHO$)\u2014reacting with nitrogen and sulfur sources under mild aqueous conditions. This pathway is particularly significant because it addresses the \"activation problem,\" producing amino acids in the form of high-energy thioesters that are pre-disposed to form peptides.Aldol Condensation and Redox RearrangementThe synthesis of threonine in this model begins with an aldol condensation between formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to generate tetrose sugars, such as erythrose, threose, and erythrulose. While conventional organic synthesis often requires strongly alkaline conditions for aldol reactions, the prebiotic model demonstrates that ammonia or existing amino acids can catalyze these steps at a more moderate pH (e.g., pH 5.2).Once formed, these four-carbon sugars react with ammonia and hydrogen sulfide in the presence of a thiol catalyst. The process involves several key steps:Dehydration: The tetrose sugar undergoes $\\beta$-dehydration to form an $\\alpha$-ketoaldehyde.Adduct Formation: The ketoaldehyde reacts with $NH_{3}$ and $H_{2}S$ to form an imine-hemithioacetal adduct.Redox Rearrangement: An intramolecular redox rearrangement of this adduct produces an activated threonine thioester.Hydrolysis/Peptidization: This thioester can either hydrolyze to free threonine or react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth.The estimated standard free energy change ($\\Delta G^{\\circ'}$) for the formation of related amino acids like homoserine via this pathway is approximately -34 kcal/mol, indicating a strong thermodynamic drive for these reactions in a prebiotic \"one-pot\" system.Computational Photochemistry and Magnesium Porphin CatalysisTheoretical studies have expanded the potential for threonine synthesis into the realm of photocatalysis, particularly on the surfaces of porphyrin-like molecules. Computational research by Nigel Aylward explores the formation of L-threonine from propyne nitrile (cyanoacetylene), carbon monoxide, water, and hydrogen on a magnesium porphin (Mg.porphin) catalyst.The Role of Photochemical ActivationThe Mg.porphin model relies on the ability of porphyrins to act as two-site catalysts, binding ligands on either the metal center or the nitrogen sites of the pyrrole rings. In the proposed mechanism for threonine, propyne nitrile and carbon monoxide bind to form axial charge-transfer complexes. The subsequent steps are highly sensitive to the energy and magnetic vector of the exciting radiation:Electronic Transition: Photochemical activation triggers an in-plane electronic transition ($HOMO$ to $LUMO$) within the porphin ring.Aziridine Formation: Under the influence of a magnetic vector, the $CO$ group moves to form a bridged aziridine-2-one ring.Cyclization and Stereocontrol: The propyne nitrile adduct combines with the activated $CO$ to form a bicyclic complex. This rigid bicyclic structure is critical for stereocontrol, as it forces subsequent water addition to occur from only one face of the molecule, thereby determining the specific (2S,3R) configuration of L-threonine.This pathway demonstrates how high-energy radiation, common on the early Earth due to the lack of an ozone layer, could be harnessed by simple organic pigments to drive the synthesis of complex, chiral amino acids from planetary gases.Extraterrestrial Evidence and Parent Body ProcessingThe presence of threonine in extraterrestrial samples provides empirical evidence that the building blocks of this amino acid\u2014and the mechanisms for its assembly\u2014are not exclusive to Earth. Carbonaceous chondrite meteorites and returned asteroid samples offer a \"fossilized\" record of prebiotic chemistry occurring in the early solar system.Threonine in the Murchison MeteoriteThe Murchison meteorite (a CM2 carbonaceous chondrite) contains a vast array of organic compounds, including a complex suite of amino acids. Recent analyses have identified ten new amino acids, including a family of nine hydroxy amino acids (HAAs) such as isoserine, homoserine, and threonine.Sample TypeL-Threonine Conc. (ppb)D-Threonine Conc. (ppb)Total Threonine (ppb)Enantiomeric Ratio (L/D)Murchison Extract173Trace-Strong L-enrichment Murchison Residue519Trace691Strong L-enrichment The detection of threonine primarily in the extract residue suggests that its hydroxyl side chain promotes strong binding to clay minerals within the meteorite matrix. While non-proteinogenic amino acids in meteorites are typically racemic, the observed L-enrichment of threonine in Murchison remains a subject of intense debate. It may reflect terrestrial contamination, but some researchers propose it could be indigenous, potentially resulting from stereoselective mineral catalysis or the influence of circularly polarized light during the aqueous alteration phase on the parent asteroid.Asteroid Sample Return: Ryugu and BennuThe JAXA Hayabusa2 and NASA OSIRIS-REx missions have provided pristine samples from asteroids Ryugu and Bennu, respectively. These samples are crucial for eliminating the variable of terrestrial contamination. Preliminary studies using three-dimensional high-performance liquid chromatography (3D-HPLC) successfully quantified several proteinogenic amino acids, including serine, alanine, and aspartic acid, in Ryugu. Although threonine was not a primary target in the initial 3D-HPLC reports, its ubiquity in related CM-type chondrites suggest it is likely present, formed via the hydrothermal processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during the melting of parent body ice.Mineral Catalysis and Geochemical EnvironmentsMinerals were the first \"enzymes\" of the prebiotic world. Their surfaces provided the necessary platform for the concentration of reactants and the lowering of activation energy barriers for complex syntheses like that of threonine.Transition Metal Sulfides: The Iron-Sulfur WorldTransition metal sulfide minerals, such as greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$), pyrite ($FeS_{2}$), and nickel-bearing sulfides, are central to the \"metabolism-first\" hypothesis. In alkaline hydrothermal vent environments, these minerals are thought to catalyze the fixation of $CO$ and $CO_{2}$ via pathways that prefigure the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Nickel isotopes found in early Earth rocks suggest that nickel may have played a more profound role than previously recognized in catalyzing the polymerization of amino acids and the fixation of carbon. Recent evidence also highlights that single amino acids, such as cysteine or histidine, can coordinate with metal ions to form catalytically active assemblies that accelerate reactions under the extreme conditions of hydrothermal vents.Clay Minerals: Montmorillonite and Concentration MechanismsMontmorillonite, a clay mineral derived from the weathering of volcanic ash, is well-known for its catalytic role in RNA oligomerization. However, its relevance to threonine synthesis lies in its adsorption properties. Clays can selectively concentrate organic molecules from the \"dilute\" prebiotic ocean, facilitating the high-density environments required for multi-body reactions like the Strecker synthesis or aldol condensations. The interlayer spacing of montmorillonite expands upon contact with water, creating a shielded microenvironment where fragile intermediates, such as the threonine precursor nitriles, can be protected from hydrolytic degradation.Environmental Drivers: Vents, Ice, and Tidal FlatsThe environmental context dictates the specific chemical potential available for synthesis.Hydrothermal Vents: These systems provide steady gradients of temperature, pH, and redox potential. Simulation experiments demonstrate that hydrothermal synthesis from $HCN$ and $H_{2}S$ can produce glycine, alanine, and serine, but threonine synthesis is often limited by the thermal instability of the molecule at temperatures exceeding $150^\\circ C$.Frozen Solutions: Freezing a reaction mixture concentrates solutes into brine pockets. Research into non-enzymatic aldol condensation has shown that complex sugars and potentially amino acids like threonine can be synthesized in ice at $-20^\\circ C$. The low temperature also serves a protective function, preventing the rapid decarboxylation that threonine undergoes at higher temperatures.Tidal Flats and Volcanic Hot Springs: These subaerial environments allow for wet-dry cycles, which are critical for the concentration of solutes and the driving of condensation reactions. Ultraviolet light in these shallow pools acts as a key energy source for the photoredox chemistry required in the cyanosulfidic pathway.Kinetic Stability and DegradationThe prebiotic relevance of threonine is constrained by its stability. Understanding how long threonine persists in the environment is essential for determining whether detected molecules are relicts of early Earth processes or the products of ongoing synthesis.Decarboxylation and Half-LivesThreonine is relatively unstable toward hydrothermal decarboxylation compared to simpler amino acids like glycine or alanine. Kinetic studies using FT-IR spectroscopy have provided the following insights into its degradation:Temperature Dependence: The rate of threonine transformation into glycine and other products increases significantly above $120^\\circ C$.pH Stability: Threonine is more thermally stable in alkaline solutions, which supports its survival in alkaline hydrothermal vent environments or the interior oceans of icy moons like Enceladus.The One-Billion Year Rule: At a temperature of 273 K (the freezing point of water), threonine is estimated to have a maximum persistence of 1 billion years. If detected in hydrothermally active ocean worlds at concentrations above 1 nM, it must have been synthesized recently.Temperature (K)EnvironmentEstimated Stability/Half-lifePrimary Degradation Product273Freezing Point$< 1$ Billion Years- 29825 \u00b0CDays (for associated RNA)- 394-433HydrothermalHours to DaysGlycine 573+Black SmokerMinutes$CO_{2}$, $NH_{3}$, Hydrocarbons These kinetic constraints suggest that for threonine to have played a role in the origin of life, its synthesis must have been either continuous or occurred in cooler, protected environments such as clay-rich sediment or ice-brine systems.Unresolved Challenges and Future Research DirectionsDespite the identification of several plausible pathways, threonine remains one of the more elusive proteinogenic amino acids in prebiotic chemistry due to several \"bottlenecks.\"The Stereochemical ChallengeThe primary challenge remains diastereoselectivity and enantioselectivity. While biology utilizes only L-threonine, prebiotic syntheses like the Strecker reaction or simple aldol condensation typically yield racemic mixtures of both threonine and its diastereomer, allothreonine. While specific catalysts like chiral pyridoxal mimics or rigid mineral surfaces show promise in inducing stereoselectivity, the transition from these laboratory-scale successes to a global geochemical phenomenon is not yet fully understood.The Dilution and Concentration ProblemThe synthesis of a four-carbon amino acid like threonine requires the collision of multiple precursors ($C_{1}, C_{2}, N, S$ sources). In the vast prebiotic ocean, the probability of such an event is extremely low. Most successful models rely on mechanisms of concentration, such as evaporation in lagoons or adsorption onto minerals like montmorillonite. However, reconciling these localized \"hotspots\" with the widespread emergence of life remains a fundamental question in origins-of-life research.Transition to MetabolismAnother significant gap is the understanding of how abiotically synthesized threonine was integrated into the first metabolic networks. Threonine\u2019s modern biosynthesis from aspartate is a complex, multi-step process involving multiple kinases and dehydrogenases. How a primitive \"protometabolism\" bridged the gap between spontaneous threonine synthesis and the regulated enzymatic production seen in the Last Universal Common Ancestor (LUCA) is still being elucidated through studies of non-enzymatic metabolic cycles.In summary, the prebiotic synthesis of threonine is no longer viewed as a random event in a \"primordial soup.\" Instead, it is understood as a product of sophisticated, systems-level chemistry involving cyanide, sulfur, and UV light, facilitated by mineral catalysis and environmental gradients. The detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials confirms that these pathways are active across the solar system, reinforcing the notion that the building blocks of life are a natural outcome of planetary and geochemical evolution. Future research will likely continue to integrate high-resolution analytical data from asteroid return missions with complex computational models to further resolve the stereochemical and concentration challenges that currently persist.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 