1998; Muchowska et al., 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface UV cyanosulfidic homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, phosphate-bearing shallow pool, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN under H2S/Cu photoredox conditions gives C2 sugar precursor glycolaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The deep research identifies UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN, facilitated by H2S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling, as the core route to glycolaldehyde in the cyanosulfidic network that also leads to threonine precursors. Mineral agents are included to satisfy the schema while preserving Cu photoredox as the key chemical driver (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface UV cyanosulfidic homologation of glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, flow-chemistry style staged addition, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "A second reductive homologation extends the carbon skeleton from C2 to C3 aldehyde.", "reasoning": "Sutherland-type cyanosulfidic chemistry generates glyceraldehyde from simpler HCN-derived feedstocks under UV/H2S/Cu photoredox conditions. The report directly links this triose chemistry to inevitable formation of the threonine aminonitrile branch product (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface triose isomerization to dihydroxyacetone", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "shallow pool, borate-rich evaporitic setting"}, "mechanism": "Triose isomerization gives the ketotriose dihydroxyacetone from glyceraldehyde with stabilization by mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "The supplied research specifically notes glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone conversion at 59% yield within the relevant prebiotic network. Borate minerals are included because the same report emphasizes borate stabilization of sugars in surface environments, while the role of the reaction here is to encode the literature-supported triose pool rather than claim direct threonine formation from DHA alone (Patel et al., 2015; Ricardo et al., 2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface branch formation of threonine aminonitrile from triose cyanosulfidic chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox with mineral concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation, cyanosulfidic flow chemistry, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Within the triose-generating network, C-C bond formation combined with cyanide addition and amination gives 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile as a branch product.", "reasoning": "The research report identifies threonine aminonitrile, 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, as an 'inevitable byproduct' of the same chemistry that yields glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone in Sutherland's cyanosulfidic protometabolism. This step is intentionally represented as a network branch rather than an over-detailed single elementary mechanism because the literature presents it as embedded systems chemistry (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cooler surface or sediment microenvironment to limit decomposition"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide/carboxylate formation to yield free amino acid.", "reasoning": "Although the deep report emphasizes aminonitrile formation more than explicit hydrolysis conditions, conversion of Strecker-type aminonitriles to amino acids is the standard completion step and is required to connect the documented precursor to the target. This step is therefore slightly connective but chemically orthodox, and cooler settings are chosen because the report highlights threonine thermal fragility (Miller, 1957; Bada, 1991; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to tetrose pool", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "ammonia-catalyzed aldol chemistry on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mildly acidic to near-neutral, around pH 5.2, wet-dry concentration cycles"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia-catalyzed aldol condensation and isomerization generate a tetrose pool including erythrose, threose, and erythrulose.", "reasoning": "The prebiotic sugar pathway described in the research begins with formaldehyde plus glycolaldehyde to produce tetrose sugars under mild aqueous conditions, with ammonia or amino acids acting as catalysts at approximately pH 5.2. This reaction is included in that literature-grounded form rather than as a generic high-pH formose step (Weber, 1987; Weber, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface dehydration of tetrose pool to alpha-ketoaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted beta-dehydration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrating evaporitic or interlayer clay microenvironment"}, "mechanism": "Tetrose sugars undergo beta-dehydration to the corresponding alpha-ketoaldehyde intermediate.", "reasoning": "The research explicitly states that tetrose sugars are converted by beta-dehydration to an alpha-ketoaldehyde prior to sulfur/nitrogen adduct formation. This step is therefore included separately to avoid the over-compression criticized in prior attempts (Weber, 1987; Weber, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Surface thiol-assisted redox rearrangement of alpha-ketoaldehyde to activated threonine thioester", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thiol-catalyzed imine-hemithioacetal formation and rearrangement", "aqueous": "true", "other": "one-pot sulfur-rich pool, anoxic, mild pH"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-ketoaldehyde forms an imine-hemithioacetal adduct with NH3 and sulfur species, then undergoes intramolecular redox rearrangement to an activated threonine thioester.", "reasoning": "This step encodes the key mechanistic detail emphasized in the report: adduct formation with NH3 and H2S followed by redox rearrangement to an activated threonine thioester. It is separated from tetrose formation and from final hydrolysis specifically to address prior under-specification (Weber, 1987; Weber, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Biochemical hydrolysis of activated threonine thioester to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cool prebiotic pool or clay-water interface; hydrolysis or transfer chemistry possible"}, "mechanism": "Activated thioester is hydrolyzed to the free amino acid under aqueous prebiotic conditions.", "reasoning": "The report states that the activated threonine thioester can hydrolyze to free threonine or participate in peptidization. This is one of the most direct literature-supported terminal steps to the target and is placed in the Biochemical setting to reflect post-surface assembly and preservation in cooler concentrated pools (Weber, 1987; Weber, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Surface cyanamide generation compatible with cyanosulfidic network", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted dehydration/photochemical processing", "aqueous": "false", "other": "drying phases in phosphate-rich pools"}, "mechanism": "Concentration and dehydration of cyanide/ammonia derivatives generate cyanamide as a condensing co-reagent.", "reasoning": "The deep report highlights cyanamide as a mutually compatible condensing agent within the same broad prebiotic systems chemistry that generates amino acids and ribonucleotide precursors. This node is included to connect the sugar and amino acid subnetworks, although the exact geochemical route here is more connective and less directly specified than the core threonine steps (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Biochemical cyanamide-assisted hydrolysis/activation of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-320K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "concentrated prebiotic pool with staged activation chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Cyanamide-mediated activation promotes nitrile hydration/hydrolysis sequence toward the free amino acid in condensed systems chemistry.", "reasoning": "This is a connective extension of the report's compatibility argument: cyanamide is identified as a condensing agent coexisting with amino acid precursor chemistry, so its use here as an activating co-reagent for aminonitrile conversion is plausible but more speculative than the direct hydrolysis step. It is retained to create one of the requested alternative paths without contradicting the literature core (Sutherland, 2016; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Photochemical Mg-porphin-catalyzed threonine formation from cyanoacetylene, CO, water, and hydrogen", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_021", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "magnesium porphin under irradiation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV/high-energy radiation, stereocontrolling bicyclic photochemical intermediate"}, "mechanism": "Photoexcited Mg-porphin forms charge-transfer complexes with cyanoacetylene and CO, enabling cyclization, water addition, and stereocontrolled assembly of threonine.", "reasoning": "The deep report specifically cites Aylward's computational Mg-porphin model for L-threonine formation from propyne nitrile, CO, water, and hydrogen via photochemical activation and bicyclic stereocontrol. This route is explicitly acknowledged as theoretical and more speculative than the surface cyanosulfidic and tetrose-thioester routes, but it is literature-grounded rather than invented (Aylward, 1999)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic aminonitrile route", "description": "HCN undergoes UV/H2S/Cu-driven reductive homologation to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde; triose chemistry yields threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Cyanosulfidic route through dihydroxyacetone pool", "description": "The triose network branches through glyceraldehyde isomerization to dihydroxyacetone before delivering threonine aminonitrile and threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Prebiotic sugar pathway via tetrose pool and thioester", "description": "Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde form tetroses, which dehydrate to alpha-ketoaldehydes and rearrange with NH3/H2S to activated threonine thioester that hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal aldehyde feed into sugar-thioester route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon chemistry supplies acetaldehyde-related reduced carbon and supports interconnected surface aldehyde chemistry feeding the tetrose-thioester pathway.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_012", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Hydrothermal formate feed into surface sugar-thioester route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction generates reduced C1 inventory represented by formate, supporting connected surface carbon chemistry that leads to tetroses and then threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rx